The error Cannot read properties of null (reading 'reset') suggests that the form element (createGroupForm) you're trying to reset in the JavaScript code doesn't exist or isn't properly referenced in the DOM.

Here’s how you can fix it:

1. Ensure Form ID is Correct

In your HTML file (create_groups.html), check that the form element has the correct ID (createGroupForm).

Make sure your form looks something like this:

<form id="createGroupForm">
    <fieldset>
        <!-- Your form fields -->
    </fieldset>
    <button type="button" onclick="submitGroupForm()" class="btn btn-primary">Create Group</button>
</form>

Ensure that the form has an id="createGroupForm" attribute as shown above.

2. Check for Element Existence Before Reset

Before calling the .reset() method, make sure that the form element exists by doing a null check. You can update your JavaScript like this:

function submitGroupForm() {
    const groupType = document.getElementById('groupType').value;
    const groupName = document.getElementById('groupName').value;
    const groupDescription = document.getElementById('groupDescription').value;

    fetch('/rest/v1/group/create', {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: {
            'Content-Type': 'application/json',
        },
        body: JSON.stringify({
            groupType: groupType,
            groupName: groupName,
            groupDescription: groupDescription
        })
    })
    .then(response => {
        if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error(`HTTP error! status: ${response.status}`);
        }
        return response.json();  // Assuming your backend sends a JSON response
    })
    .then(data => {
        console.log('Group creation response:', data);

        document.getElementById('responseMessage').innerText = "Success: Group created successfully";
        document.getElementById('responseMessage').classList.add('alert-success');
        document.getElementById('responseMessage').style.display = 'block';

        // Reset the form, but check if it exists first
        const form = document.getElementById('createGroupForm');
        if (form) {
            form.reset();
        }
    })
    .catch(error => {
        console.error('Error:', error);
        document.getElementById('responseMessage').innerText = `Error: Failed to create group, details: ${error}`;
        document.getElementById('responseMessage').classList.add('alert-danger');
        document.getElementById('responseMessage').style.display = 'block';
    });
}

This way, the script will first check if the form exists before calling .reset().

3. Debugging the Form ID

If the error persists, it could mean that the form element is not rendering properly or is missing. In that case:

Double-check that the form element exists in your HTML.

Make sure the form's id matches the one being referenced in the JavaScript (createGroupForm).

Inspect the page source (right-click and select "View Page Source") to see if the form is rendered properly in the DOM.


